Day 5 I feel better, but still have sweats, diarrhea and intermittent nausea.

Several days later my left groin was painful.  I went to my orthopedic Dr. and an MRI showed stress fracture to the pelvis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Loss of appetite, dizziness, fatigue, joint pain, muscle aches, headaches, neuropathy- started winter of 2017 through currently (see question 5). Fall of 2018 anxiety increased, food smells caused nausea, previous symptoms are getting worse. Fall of 2019 (Oct 14) heart flutters occurred- heart monitor used for 24 hours. Winter of 2019 (Dec 4) diagnosed with P.O.T.S. has developed food sensitivities. Spring 2019 (03/26/2019) Dr diagnosed patient with fibromyalgia. Oct. 8, 2018 went to Dr because of shortness of breath
LAB_DATA: blood work (14 tests) 02-14-2019 Dr.; EMG test 03/14/2019 Dr - results normal; ultrasound in lower legs and feet for neuropathy 03/26/2019 - results normal; Visited Dr for shortness of breath (10/08/2019) did a chest x-ray and blood work (cbc, vit B met, Vit D, tsh, D-dimer) - came back normal; On 10/14/2019 had a 24 hour heart monitor in place- results from Dr (primary/pediatrician) looked ok but referred us to a pediatric cardiologist for a second opinion. Results from Dr (11/21/2019 visit) were heart is fine but the visceral nervous system was not working properly- he thought it was P.O.T.S.. Referred us to nurse practitioner (NP) for further study. On 11/15/2019 had a 30 day heart monitor in place per Dr for further data. On 11/21/2019 had a follow up with Dr to discuss results from the visit to the pediatric cardiologist Dr. Had a B-12 blood test done at this visit and results came back normal. On 12/04/2019 had an appointment with NP and she diagnosed patient with P.OT.S.. She had enough data from the 30 day heart monitor and discontinued use. Results from the 30 day heart monitor were a heart rate at rest of 105 and a heart rage moving around 140.
OTHER_MEDS: D-Amphetamine ER 20 mg salt combo cp

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The next morning after receiving my flu vaccination my mouth started to feel sore.  Over the next couple of days I developed 6+ canker sores on the inside of my mouth, a couple under my tongue, a couple along the inside of my lower lip and a couple along the inner part of my upper lip.  I have never had more than 1 canker sore at once and haven't had a single canker sore in several years, I can't even remember the last time I had one.   After a few days of severe discomfort and having to adjust my diet, I finally got a mouth rinse for mouth sores and that eventually helped relieve symptoms.  The canker sores have cleared up.  Maybe it is totally unrelated, but these mouth sores seemed oddly coincidental to receiving the flu vaccination.
CUR_ILL: Got a 102 Fever and was sick in the beginning of December 2019  for about a week but was feeling healthier at the time of the vaccination.

Erythema multiforme; Erythema multiforme; papular lesions; papular lesions; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of erythema multiforme in a 2-year-old female patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose and Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Flu vaccine and not applicable after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced erythema multiforme (serious criteria GSK medically significant), erythema multiforme (serious criteria GSK medically significant), papular rash and papular rash. Rechallenge with Flu vaccine was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the erythema multiforme and papular rash were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the erythema multiforme and papular rash were unknown.   The reporter considered the erythema multiforme and papular rash to be related to Flu vaccine. The reporter considered the erythema multiforme and papular rash to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of erythema multiforme (EM) in a female patient aged 2-year-old who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to result section reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of study that aimed to describe reported Erythema multiforme, Stevens Johnson syndrome, and toxic epidermal necrolysis (EM/SJS/TEN) after vaccines during 1st October 1999 through 31st December 2017 (among reports received by CDC and FDA through April 27, 2018). Country reports of EM/SJS/TEN received by the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) were identified and compared the relative frequency of EM/SJS/TEN reported to VAERS by vaccine, to better understand if there were any concerning patterns of reported EM/SJS/TEN (e.g., after a specific vaccine, or among a particular age group) or other emerging safety concerns. [In this study, it was reported AEs occurring after vaccination can be reported to VAERS, a national spontaneous reporting system established in 1990 to monitor AEs that is jointly administered by the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and Prevention and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]. No information on patient's medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided.  On an unspecified date, an unknown period after vaccination, the patient was noted with EM. On an unspecified date between 1st October 1999 through 31st December 2017 (among reports received by CDC and FDA through 27th April 2018), the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date between 1st October 1999 through 31st December 2017 (received as of 27th April 2018), an unknown period after vaccination, the patient was again noted with EM. [In this study, the resulting reports for reports of EM/SJS/TEN that were diagnosed by physicians (reported by a physician, or a physician's diagnosis was documented in available medical records) were received. For reports of symptoms consistent with EM/SJS/TEN, but without a physician's diagnosis, we defined EM as papular lesions, classically with a ringed (‘‘targetoid") appearance, usually beginning peripherally and then spreading to the torso, that could involve the palms of the hands and/or soles of the feet, without mucosal lesions. Most reports of EM/SJS/TEN described onset of symptoms within 14 days of vaccination] Treatment was unknown. Outcome of the event was not reported. The authors commented, "Of the 4 persons we describe who previously experienced EM or SJS after vaccination, two experienced another episode of EM or SJS after the same vaccine (positive rechallenge). Our estimated reporting rates of EM/SJS/TEN after varicella and influenza vaccines were well below this figure (i.e., the highest estimate was 1.0 report of EM per million doses of varicella vaccine distributed), a notable observation considering that varicella vaccine was one of the most commonly reported vaccines after which EM/SJS/TEN occurred. Despite potentially underestimating rates, our data suggest that EM/SJS/TEN is reported no more frequently after vaccination than after known causes of these conditions. Importantly, while EM/SJS/TEN can occur after vaccination, previous post-marketing analyses and case-control studies demonstrate that vaccination itself does not increase the likelihood of these conditions". The authors concluded "EM/SJS/TEN were rarely reported after vaccination; data mining identified a known association between EM and smallpox vaccine". This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

postherpetic neuralgia; shingles; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of an unknown age. central retinal artery occlusion of the left eye; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of an unknown age. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On or around 17-OCT-2017, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (exact dose, dose number, route and site of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported), for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered an acute onset of left eye vision loss. The patient was admitted to the hospital and she was ultimately diagnosed with central retinal artery occlusion of the left eye and was completely blind in her left eye, at the reporting time. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to vaccination. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitation and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, the patient suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event was reported as not recovered. The relatedness between the event and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was reported as related.  Upon internal review, the event of central retinal artery occlusion of the left eye was considered to be medically significant.  The event of central retinal artery occlusion of the left eye was considered to be disabling.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient (accompanied by mother) received 8 vaccines in the immunization clinic at 2:50pm. He reported mild dizziness within 3 minutes and put his head between his legs in the IZ exam room. After about 5 minutes he reported he felt better. He declined laying down on a yoga mat on the floor. I instructed him, with his mother, to sit in the waiting room for 10 more minutes before he left. The exam room was very warm and the waiting room would be cooler. He reported feeling okay when he stood up from the chair in the exam room. When we walked into the waiting room, he reported he felt dizzy. I held his arm to help him into a chair and he stumbled and then fell to the ground, slightly assisted by my arm. He did not strike his head or injure any part of his body. He appeared to lose consciousness for about 5-10 seconds and then awoke. I called for another nurse and instructed him to remain laying on the ground for 5 minutes. When he reported feeling no longer dizzy, I helped him into a chair where he sat for 15 minutes and drank juice. He left with his mother in her private vehicle after reporting no symptoms for 15 minutes.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the flu vaccine in my IT department. We have nurses that work in our department that administer the flu shot to employees who work in this off site location. The injection felt and hurt normally as it would with any shot. That night I felt very tired, sore, and the next day stayed home from work. By the end of the day Thursday 10.3 and into 10.4 I was unable to move my left arm without significant pain. I could not get dressed independently, could not lift things, open doors, or pick up a child. I could not sleep the night of 10.3. I went to occupational health on 10.4 at Hospital who deals with our employee occupational health issues. I was seen by an APRN. It was noted that the injection was not given in the correct location (too high). I was put on high dose prednisone. I subsequently followed up with my own PCP and was told the same and given the same regimen. After the prednisone was over the pain came back, so I went to see an orthopedic doctor. I have had an xray and an MRI now. I am still having pain in my left shoulder.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: In the middle of the night 12/19/19 approx 1:00am  (approx 16hrs after the flu shot, I moved from the couch - 18inches high - to bed  -29inches high, after walking room to room for a minute eg using the bathroom, turning off lights; After getting up on the bed, I leaned on my left hip to lie down and as I went to put my head on the pillow it felt like the bed and room were moving.  I had a sensation of falling.  This passed once I settled in bed.      The same thing happened going to bed that night Thurs 12/19/19.   12/20/19 I had the sensation while turning over.  For one week from Weds 12/18/19 I had a vague sensation it was starting a few times so I moved slowly when transitioning/turning over.   I had no trouble walking, driving, shopping,  shovelling snow.   I did not faint.  I also woke up with a headache -  I believe it was Sat 12/21/19  This is not uncommon but also not a regular thing.  I took 1000mg Tylenol and it resolved in a few hours.  My throat/voice were raspy as if I were coming down with a cold for a day and this passed.
LAB_DATA: No tests; No labs.  I did not inform my NP as symptoms were brief and I managed them.  The first few days I thought it was Eagle's Syndrome symptoms but it was strange it happened late at night and that is not typical of my usual symptoms.   The usual symptom is foreign body sensation in my throat and wooziness with head position if my head is held sharply left or right too long.     I then realized it cooincided with the day of my flu shot.
OTHER_MEDS: Magnesium 250mg once or twice/day am&pm  TTD: 500mg some days D3 5000IU  once per day most days CoQ10 200mg once per day most days
CUR_ILL: I felt well on 12/18/19. I have Eagle's syndrome, vascular type.  This is an elongated and calcified ligament in the base of my skull that runs between my inner & outer carotid artery on the right side of my neck.  My Eagle's symtoms had been worse in 2019 eg  foreign body sensation in my throat, very tired and heavy feeling neck.  Over the past 9 years I  have been unable to hold my head to the right more than a few seconds without feeling uncomfortable and sometimes feeling like I could pass out.  I avoid turning my head sharply to the left because it makes the right side uncomfortable.  It feels like a twisting feeling.  This is NOT constant and since I avoid holding my head in those positions I did not have these sensations in December 2019.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Neonatal abstinence syndrome; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 02-Jan-2020, concerning a female neonate subject. The subject's mother was 30-year-old, female pregnant subject, of body weight 148 lbs, height 66 inches and body mass index (BMI) 23.9 enrolled in,  a prospective observational safety study. The age of subject's father was not reported.  The mother's current medical conditions included anxiety, morning sickness and opioid abuse (as reported).  The mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for pregnancy, buprenorphine for opioid abuse, Bonjesta (doxylamine succinate, pyridoxine hydrochloride) for morning sickness and escitalopram for anxiety.  The subject's mother had three previous pregnancies which included one full term live birth, one elective abortion and one spontaneous abortion. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs) and had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject's mother did not use tobacco or alcohol during pregnancy.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 09-Mar-2019. The mother's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 14-Dec-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 10-Dec-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 05-Jun-2019, the subject's mother underwent first trimester screen with nuchal translucency scan. There was no MCM noted.  On 03-Jul-2019, the subject's mother underwent second trimester alpha-fetoprotein (APF) screen. There was no MCM noted.  On 19-Sep-2019, at approximately 27 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Flucelvax QIVc [Influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, batch number: 259809, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as ‘Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  On 13-Dec-2019, at gestational age of 40.4 weeks, mother vaginally delivered a live birth female neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 3118 grams, body length and head circumference were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores at one minute was 8, at five minutes was 9 and at 10 minutes no data was provided. No MCM was identified at birth. However, the subject developed neonatal abstinence syndrome due to which was admitted to pediatrics (PEDS). No further information was provided.  At the time of this report, the outcome of the event neonatal abstinence syndrome was not reported.  Per company, the event of neonatal abstinence syndrome was considered serious due to criterion of medical significance.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIV.  This case is linked to case number 202000006 (corresponding mother case).  Company comment: A female neonate patient was exposed to Flucelvax QIVc after maternal receipt of vaccine at 10 weeks of gestation. The mother's current medical conditions included opioid abuse. Reportedly, the subject developed drug withdrawal syndrome neonatal. Causal role of the suspect vaccine is assessed as not related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: A female neonate patient was exposed to Flucelvax QIVc after maternal receipt of vaccine at 10 weeks of gestation. The mother's current medical conditions included opioid abuse. Reportedly, the subject developed drug withdrawal syndrome neonatal. Causal role of the suspect vaccine is assessed as not related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.
OTHER_MEDS: PRENATAL VITAMINS [MINERALS NOS;VITAMINS NOS]; BUPRENORPHINE; BONJESTA; ESCITALOPRAM

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Urinary tract infection; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 02-Jan-2020, concerning a 32-year-old female, pregnant subject of body weight 97 lbs, height 63 in and body mass index (BMI) 17.2, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's current medical history included the first occurrence of urinary tract infection and low BMI.   The subject's concomitant medications included: OB complete (pregnancy multivitamins and multiminerals) for healthy pregnancy and ampicillin for urinary tract infection.   The subject had two previous pregnancies which included one full term live birth and one spontaneous abortion. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-May-2019. The subject's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 26-Feb-2020 and corrected EDD (CEDD) was not reported. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 21-Aug-2019, the subject underwent first trimester screen and cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and no MCM was noted.   On 09-Sep-2019, at approximately 15 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Afluria QIV [influenza vaccine, batch number: P100110950, dose, expiration date, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunization. On the same day, the subject underwent second trimester screen and no MCM was noted.  On an unknown date in Dec-2019, the subject experienced the second occurence of urinary tract infection.  From 16-Dec-2019 to 23-Dec-2019, the subject was treated with ampicillin at dose of 500 mg, every day, orally.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome for the second occurence of urinary tract infection was not reported.  The event of urinary tract infection was considered serious due to criterion of medical significance.  The causality assessment was not provided.  Company comment: A 32-year-old pregnant subject experienced urinary tract infection (UTI), associated with administration of Afluria QIV. The vaccine was administered at 15 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. UTIs are common during pregnancy, because growing uterus makes pressure on the bladder and urinary tract. Although causality was highly confounded by subject's medical history of UTI, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: A 32-year-old pregnant subject experienced urinary tract infection (UTI), associated with administration of Afluria QIV. The vaccine was administered at 15 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. UTIs are common during pregnancy, because growing uterus makes pressure on the bladder and urinary tract. Although causality was highly confounded by subject's medical history of UTI, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.

LAB_DATA: A temporal biopsy of both sides was performed by a vascular surgeon along with many other tests including MRI.  I am currently being treated by a Rheumatologist for long term care.  I don't know if these events are a coincidence or not but I do know that it all seemed to happen after having the Shingrix vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Strong flu-like symptoms for 48 hours after vaccination.  Neck discomfort began perhaps 1 month after vaccination .. eventually realizing there were one or more swollen lymph nodes.  This was accompanying by varying degrees of vertigo.    This has come and gone since the vaccination.  I have sought medical assistance though I have not been diagnosed with anything more than "swollen lymph node".   My medical "treatment" has included blood work in october and december, ultrasund of neck soft tissue and carotid arteries.  Xray of cervical spine.    These test as referred by my primary care physicial.   I have also seen an ENT specialist who believes the lymph node is resolving, but wishes to do additonal balance testing  in regards to the vertigo/dizziness I have experienced.
LAB_DATA: Bloodwork :  on or about 10/24/2019                               dec 28, 2019  X-ray of cervical spine:  12/4/2019 Ultrasound neck, soft tissues:  12/5/2019 Ultrasound of carotid arteries.  12/28/2019 ENT doctor:  hearing test (normal for age).   1/2/2020

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Employee stated after 20 minutes when she received 3rd HEP - b shot, she felt nauseous and hot. Later she stated that she vomited twice. Clinic was contacted condition of employee was related to person on line. That person talked with employee, asked questions  employee stated that now she was having chest discomfort. Clinic advised that 911 should be called or someone transport her to the ER. 911 was called, Fire Department responded and employee to the ER. Unknown of the treatment employee received.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Flu-like symptoms day after first injection (12/8/19)---extreme muscle ache, fatigue, headache. On 6th day post-injection (12/13/19), upper right quadrant abdominal pain continuing thru 8th day (12/15/19) when I went to Hospital emergency room. I had abdominal pain and increasing, spreading right-sided only numbness in entire body from right ankle all the way upward to right ear. Abdominal pain had lasted for 3 days to that point and the numbness began mid-morning on the 8th day and became worse & more widespread by late afternoon.
LAB_DATA: ER staff performed ultrasound & CT scan of abdomen with normal results on 12/15/19. Complete blood panel also done with no unusual abnormality. Gallbladder & kidney problems ruled out. Released to go home 12/15/19 with diagnosis of emerging shingles outbreak. Given Rxs for Famvir 500mg TID,  Hydrocodone/APAP prn
OTHER_MEDS: Metformin, Gabapentin, Verapamil, Propranolol, Vitamin D, Keppra, Levothyroxine, Maxalt, Meloxicam, Ibuprofen, Biotin
ALLERGIES: None known; Intolerance to Morphine/Vicodin---gives a headache

Patient states that she has ringing in the ears that started about a day after receiving her first dose of Shingrix.  She stated that she never experienced any episode of tinnitus before.  She denies being sick or receiving any other vaccinations at the same time.  She did not experience any issues prior to leaving the pharmacy.  She saw her primary doctor, who advised her to still receive the second dose of the vaccine and advised seeing an ENT.  She said she saw an ENT but could not recall his name.  She received the second dose of Shingrix on 09/29/2019.  She noted that on the VIS under section it notes that ringing in the ears is possible.  I explained it was in relation to signs and symptoms of fainting as a result of vaccination.
LAB_DATA: Patient said she received a hearing test at the ENT and the results were a mild hearing loss consistent with her age.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The morning after shot I awoke to excruciating cramps in both calves (never experienced before) both calves very sore to touch after cramps closed, muscle pain proceeded up my legs to thighs (front and back) much like pain from excessive exercise, then to my buttocks. I now have extreme pain in my right leg with some pain in my left. I'm very active (or was) and am now having pain to use a cane due to muscle weakness, particularly in my right leg. My cardiologist retired the end of Nov. My P.C.P is not of the country. I'm in the midst of arranging for new doctors. I've been keeping pain at bay (through trial and error) with prednisone, hydrocodone, gabapentin and naproxen sodium. None of which can be good for my long range health care. Sleeping is difficult due to pain and there is a feelin of heaviness in my legs. I fear (my greatest fear) is that this condition is here to stay. I would much rather have the flu (which can be diagnosed) than go through these last few weeks. I failed to mention that the pain is exreme in my right groin area and if I do walk or try to do chores the pain is unmanageable even with the above mentioned meds. P.S. couldn't the gov. afford little more legible form?
SEVERE MUSCLE ACHES - LEGS, ALL OVER. SEVERE CHILLS HEADACHE FATIGUE ... FOR 2 FULL DAYS FOLLOWING SHOT

No additional AE information; improperly stored VARIVAX was administrated to a patient; This spontaneous report has been received from a medical assistant referring to a 12 months old male patient. Information about the patient's past drug and medical history, as well as concurrent conditions and allergies were not provided.  On 30-DEC-2019, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) injection, subcutaneously, lot number S024366, expiration date on 06-AUG-2021 (concentration, dose number, and anatomical location were not reported), for prophylaxis, that had been improperly stored in a temperature of 6 Fahrenheit degrees to 14 Fahrenheit degrees (14.1 Fahrenheit degrees) for 30 minutes, and 15 Fahrenheit degrees to 46 Fahrenheit degrees (26.6 Fahrenheit degrees) for 4 hours and 18 minutes; varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) was reconstituted with sterile diluent (lot number and expiration date were not reported). No symptoms and no additional adverse events were reported. There was not previous temperature excursion and the temperature was recorded by a data logger.  The outcome of the event was unknown.

after getting the "first round of M-M-R II vaccine required by his school," she noticed post vaccination that her son developed a "respiratory tract infection"; The patient developed "persistent cough."; This spontaneous report has been received from a consumer, who was the patient's mother, referring to a male patient of unknown age. Information about the patient's pertinent medical history included a pre-existing condition such as sleep apnea. His concomitant medication and previous drug reactions or allergies were not provided by the reporter.  On an unspecified date, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) required by his school for prophylaxis (strength, dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number, and expiration date were not provided by the reporter).  Subsequently, the reporter noticed that the patient developed a respiratory tract infection and a persistent cough.  It was unknown if any treatment was given for the events, if any laboratory diagnostics/studies were performed or if the patient sought medical attention.  At the time of reporting, the outcome of the aforementioned events was not provided.  The causality assessment between therapy with measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (M-M-R II) and the reported events was not provided.  Upon internal review, respiratory tract infection was determined to be a medically significant event.  This is one of two reports received from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2001USA000655:

Cold antibody autoimmune hemolytic anemia; This is a literature report from the Clinical Case Reports. This is the first reported case of cold antibody autoimmune hemolytic anemia due to anti-Pr autoantibodies attributed to Pneumococcal vaccination in an adult patient. The patient presented 1 week after receiving the vaccination with low hemoglobin, jaundice, and dyspnea with no prior history of anemia. Extensive workup including ruling out infectious and malignant causes was unremarkable, and his treatment consisted of transfusions and a course of steroids. An autoantibody anti-Pr was identified with persistence but decreased reactivity up to 3 months after his initial presentation.  The patient is a 72-year-old man who presented with jaundice and increasing dyspnea on exertion and was found to be anemic with hemoglobin of 7.4 g/dL. His symptoms began approximately 1 week after receiving the pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) vaccination. The patient had been in stable health with a documented hemoglobin level of 13.9 g/dL at the time of his implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD) placement 2 months prior. His past medical history included congestive heart failure with ejection fraction of 10%, type II diabetes mellitus, and hypertension. His medication regimen had been stable for several years and included low strength aspirin, naproxen, lisinopril, carvedilol, furosemide, potassium chloride, simvastatin, metformin, glipizide, gabapentin, omeprazole, docusate sodium, folic acid, and a daily multivitamin. He had no prior history of anemia and had never before required a blood transfusion. At presentation, the patient was jaundiced with stable vital signs (temperature of 98.8 degree F, heart rate of 88 beats/minute, blood pressure of 112/61 mm Hg, and oxygen saturation of 97% on room air). Laboratory results were significant for a low RBC count (2.60 M/CUMM; normal range: 4.15-5.75 M/ CUMM), reticulocyte count of 0.5 percent, elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH; 445 U/L; normal range 125-243 U/L), decreased haptoglobin (<8 mg/dL; normal range 30-200 mg/ dL), and elevated total bilirubin (5.2 mg/dL; normal level up to 1.2 mg/dL). A peripheral blood smear was remarkable for spherocytosis. Direct antiglobulin testing was negative on two separate occasions for IgG as well as complement C3 components. A cold autoantibody was identified that reacted to all panel cells. The antibody was nonreactive with enzyme-treated RBCs and identified as anti-Pr The patient was diagnosed with cold antibody AIHA most likely secondary to recent administration of the pneumococcal vaccination (PREVNAR 13). Further workup was unremarkable including the following: hepatitis serology testing, serum protein electrophoresis with immunofixation, general flow cytometry screening, Cryoglobulin testing, iron studies, folate, and B12. Parvovirus showed positive IgG and negative IgM, consistent with prior infection. Polymerase chain reaction testing for Parvovirus was negative. Computed tomography scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis demonstrated several borderline mediastinal lymph nodes measuring up to 1.3 cm, a left implantable cardioverter- defibrillator (ICD) in place, a moderately enlarged heart, no obvious lung abnormalities or nodules, and a normal appearing liver and spleen with no abdominal or pelvic lymphadenopathy. He had a white blood cell count of 3.5 K/ CUMM (normal range 3.3-10.5 K/CUMM) and platelet count of 215 K/CUMM (normal range 150-400 K/CUMM). During his hospitalization, the patient's hemoglobin dropped to 6.6 g/dL, and his bilirubin increased to 6.6 mg/ dL with a normal direct bilirubin of 0.5 mg/dL. The patient was transfused with one unit of packed red blood cells and discharged home in stable condition with a post-transfusion hemoglobin level of 7.5 g/dL. At follow-up, 11 days after his transfusion, his hemoglobin had dropped to 6.8 g/dL. He received two additional units of packed red blood cells with rise in hemoglobin to 9.3 g/dL. The patient was also treated with a course of prednisone with taper over 2 months. His hemoglobin level continued to rise, reaching 13.8 g/dL 3 months after discontinuation of steroid treatment. A blood sample at that time showed persistence of anti-Pr, though with overall decreased reactivity strengths. The patient's laboratory studies showed no evidence of hemolysis with a normal LDH of 187 U/L and RBC of 4.61 M/CUMM. Information on the batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available (hemolytic anemia occurred one week post vaccination with Prevnar 13 and positive cold autoantibody identified against Pr antigen the antigenic determinants of which have been found on almost all RBCs), it cannot be excluded that Pneumococcal vaccination with Prevnar 13 may elicit the formation of Pr specific autoantibody thus triggered the occurrence of cold antibody autoimmune hemolytic anemia.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Eleven days after administration of vaccination, patient presented with measles-like rash all over body and cold symptoms

Shortly after receiving the flu vaccine on 12/30/19 she experienced seeing white spots and then feeling like she was going to pass out.  She experienced a frontal headache after.  Later on in the evening she verbalized passing out at the dinner table.  She developed an urticarial rash on her upper back on 12/31/19.  She had several episodes of syncope on 12/31, each lasting a few minutes 9am, 1:30pm and 3:30pm.  After those episodes she sought medical evaluation.  Unsure if these events were caused by influenza vaccination or was triggered by influenza vaccination but felt the need to report.
LAB_DATA: 1/1/20 to 1/4/20 cardiac monitor, cardiology consult with recommendations for a tilt table, ECHO, EKG, Carotid doppler, EEG scheduled at a later date, MRI to be scheduled at a later date as an outpatient. General chemistry, CBC,  endocrine and thyroid studies performed.  No acute abnormalities seen in any testing or lab results .  Outpatient referral for neurologist.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The Vaccine (VARIVAX) was repeated on 15-NOV-2019 (third dose).; No adverse effects reported; Patient was vaccinated with Varivax reconstituted with expired sterile diluent; This spontaneous report was received from a nurse and refers to an 18-year-old patient of unknown gender. No information regarding the patient's concurrent condition, past medical history, concomitant medications, and drug reactions or allergies was provided.  On 07-OCT-2019, the patient was vaccinated with a second dose of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) 1 dosage form for prophylaxis (lot number R034396, has been verified to be a valid, expiration date reported and validated as 27-NOV-2020) (concentration, frequency of vaccination scheme, route and anatomical location of vaccination were not reported).  On 08-OCT-2019 (reported as on the next day), it was realized that an expired sterile diluent ( lot number R022280 has been verified to be a valid, expiration date reported and validated as 06-OCT-2019) was used for the reconstitution of the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) vaccine used to vaccinate the patient the prior day (expired product administered). No adverse effects were reported.  Follow-up information was received from the registered nurse on 27-DEC-2019. The patient's exact date of birth and gender were provided.  On 07-OCT-2019, at 2:30pm, the male patient was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) subcutaneously on the left arm and he also received meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA) via intramuscular on the left deltoid (concomitant therapy), both as immunization.   The patient did not require any treatment for the reported events.   It was also reported that the vaccination was repeated on 15-NOV-2019 (inappropriate schedule of product administration) and that there was not any temperature excursion as a result of reading the Digital Data-logger.

After got vaccination, the patient developed incurable eczema; This spontaneous report has been received from a consumer referring to her daughter, a female of unknown age. Information about the patient's past drug and medical history, as well as her concomitant therapies and allergies were not reported.  On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II) injection (concentration, dosage, anatomical location, administration route, lot number, and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis. Subsequently, the patient developed incurable eczema. The outcome of the event was unknown. Therefore, the patient was not recovered from the event at the reporting time.   It was unknown if the patient sought medical attention, or if she performed any laboratories or studies.  The causality assessment between Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II) and the occurred event was not reported.  This is one of two cases from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2001USA000651:

Flublok Quadrivalent was administered to a 12 year-old child, no AE; Initial information received on 09-Dec-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a other health professional.  This case involves a 12 years old patient who received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV] (lot QFAA1959 and expiry date: 30-Jun-2020) via intramuscular route in the right deltoid, on an unknown date.  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  Concomitant medications included HPV VACCINE (HPV VACCINE) for Immunisation.  It was a case of actual medication error due to inappropriate age at vaccine administration. It was reported that Flublok Quadrivalent was administered to a 12 year-old child.  At the time of reporting, no adverse event was reported.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holders compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. 2- doses of Fluzone High-Dose during the same season, No AE; accidentally administered the Fluzone High-Dose in error not the pneumonia vaccine, no AE; Initial information received on 11-Dec-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse.  This case involves a 67 year old female patient who received two doses of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH DOSE] during the same season due to the consumer was to receive a pneumonia vaccine but was given a dose of Fluzone High-Dose instead.  The patient's medical history, past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  On 01-Nov-2019, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE (lot UJ301AA and expiry date 24-Jun-2020) via intramuscular route in the left deltoid. On 10-Dec-2019 she also received an extra dose of the same vaccine  with an unknown batch number via intramuscular route at an unknown administration site. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I went to my physician's office to receive my first Shingrix injection. The injection was given at approximately 2:00 pm. At approximately 8:00 pm that same evening, I began to get chills. By midnight, I was running a temperature of 103.6. I took Ibuprofen and Acetaminophen to lower my fever. Last night, I had a night sweat that soaked my entire bed, blankets and comforter. Today, almost two days later I feel awful. I did research the side effects and I was aware that some people get a low grade fever and chills. I had no problem with that. But to get a fever of 103.6, I feel is dangerous. If it had gone any higher, I would have had my spouse take me to the emergency room. I did have the shingles when I was in my early 20's. To be honest, I would have rather had another bout of shingles than the side effects of this drug. My physician's office advised me to come back somewhere in the vicinity of 4 months for the second dose. They can forget it. I would not recommended this medication and I will be advising friends and family to avoid receiving it. I'm on day 3 and feel like I was beat up. Although at the writing of this report I'm not running a fever, I feel beat down. I'm weak and have no appetite. I'm hoping this will subside soon. Again, I'm sorry I received this medication and will let everyone I know to avoid it.
OTHER_MEDS: Crestor 20 mg Lexapro 10 mg; Zyrtec 10 mg

Patient reported arm discomfort, numbness and tingling the same day as vaccination occurred. Discomfort is ongoing and Pain Clinic provider indicated the following in -e-consult note: Therefore the symptoms are more likely c/w small cutaneous nerve damage from either needle/hydrostatic pressure damage during vaccination despite normal EMG as the symptoms match temporally and anatomically with injection time and site and small fiber damage is often not seen on EMG's. Rule of thumb for small fiber dmg is 90% better in 90 days and 99% better in a year. As long as the condition is slowly improving I would not recommend further modalities such as nerve blocks or even cutaneous infiltration and suggest continued watchful waiting and/ or symptomatic care with reassurance that this condition should slowly improve. If condition worsens, consider neuro econsult/consult and then can consider local infiltration/nerve blocks in addition to pharm and MH related pain control techniques. Please let me know if you have questions.
HISTORY: Hx of bone spurs removed from site near injection site

The day after I got the shot, when I went to get out of bed in the morning, I felt like I was going to pass out, so I waited. I got to the bathroom, sat down on the toilet and had some diarrhea and then I started to burn up, freeze and shake all at the same time. I've never had that happen before. I didn't know what was happening to me and I got scared. When I tried to stand up, I couldn't. My legs had no muscle strength. So I sat on the toilet for about 20 minutes, burning up, freezing, and shaking, all at the same time. Then I was finally able to get up. I put a wet wash cloth on my forehead and laid down in bed cause I was still burning up, freezing and shaking. After an hour or more I finally stopped shaking, freezing and burning up. I called the pharmacy and told the pharmacist what happened. She said I probably had a reaction to the shot and to call my Dr. I called the Dr. and they were out to lunch, so I called later at 2. I told the gal what happened and she said she would tell my Dr. and get back to me. They finally called back after 5 and said I should take some Tylenol. By that time I was feeling better, but I tool some Tylenol anyway. The next day, I was feeling almost back to normal. That was so scary for me since I was home alone and didn't know what the heck was happening to me!
OTHER_MEDS: Caltrate Irbesartan, Atorvastatin, Biotin, Fish oil
PRIOR_VAX: Flu shot - 70yrs, 11-7-19- Had bad diarrhea the following 2 mornings

SYMPTOM_TEXT: respiratory failure; stevens johnson syndrome; toxic epidermal necrolysis; Initial information received on 31-DEC-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious literature case.   This case is linked to cases 2020SA001262, 2020SA001225, 2020SA001235 and 2020SA001250 (Same reporter).  The following is verbatim from the article:  Background: Since the last review of vaccine safety surveillance data for erythema multiforme (EM), Stevens Johnson syndrome (SJS), SJS/TEN, and toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN) (EM/SJS/TEN), over 37 new vaccines have been introduced. We sought to describe reported EM/SJS/TEN after vaccines during 1999-2017.  Methods: We identified reports of EM/SJS/TEN received by the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) during 1999-2017. We stratified analysis by condition (EM, SJS, or TEN), and analyzed reports by serious or non-serious status, sex, age group, time from vaccination to symptom onset, exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN, and vaccines administered. We used Empirical Bayesian data mining to detect vaccine-AE pairs reported more frequently than expected. Results: Of 466,027 reports to VAERS during 1999-017, we identified 984 reports of EM, 89 reports of SJS, 6 reports of SJS/TEN, and 7 reports of TEN. Few reports of EM (9%), and most reports of SJS (52%), SJS/TEN (100%), and TEN (100%) were serious. Overall, 55% of reports described males, 48% described children aged 4 years; 58% of EM/SJS/TEN occurred 7 days after vaccination. Few reports (5%) described exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN. Overall, childhood vaccines (e.g., combined measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine) were most commonly reported. We identified 6 deaths; 4 were exposed to medications associated with EM/SJS/TEN. EM after smallpox vaccine was reported disproportionately among people aged 19 - 49 years.  Conclusions: EM/SJS/TEN were rarely reported after vaccination; data mining identified a known association between EM and smallpox vaccine. Erythema multiforme; Initial information received on 31-Dec-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from other healthcare professional issued from a literature article.   This case is linked to cases 2020SA001262, 2020SA001250, 2020SA001235 and 2020SA001256 (same reporter).  Abstract:  Since the last review of vaccine safety surveillance data for erythema multiforme (EM), Stevens Johnson syndrome (SJS), SJS/TEN, and toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN) (EM/SJS/TEN), over 37 new vaccines have been introduced. We sought to describe reported EM/SJS/TEN after vaccines during 1999-2017. Methods: We identified reports of EM/SJS/TEN received by the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) during 1999-2017. We stratified analysis by condition (EM, SJS, or TEN), and analyzed reports by serious or non-serious status, sex, age group, time from vaccination to symptom onset, exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN, and vaccines administered. We used data mining to detect vaccine-AE pairs reported more frequently than expected. Results: Of 466,027 reports to VAERS during 1999-017, we identified 984 reports of EM, 89 reports of SJS, 6 reports of SJS/TEN, and 7 reports of TEN. Few reports of EM (9%), and most reports of SJS (52%), SJS/TEN (100%), and TEN (100%) were serious. Overall, 55% of reports described males, 48% described children aged 4 years; 58% of EM/SJS/TEN occurred 7 days after vaccination. Few reports (5%) described exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN. Overall, childhood vaccines (e.g., combined measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine) were most commonly reported. We identified 6 deaths; 4 were exposed to medications associated with EM/SJS/TEN. EM after smallpox vaccine was reported disproportionately among people aged 19 - 49 years. Conclusions: EM/SJS/TEN were rarely reported after vaccination; data mining identified a known association between EM and smallpox vaccine. Erythema multiforme; Initial information received on 31-Dec-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from other healthcare professional issued from a literature article.    This case is linked to cases 2020SA001262, 2020SA001225, 2020SA001235 and 2020SA001256 (same reporter).  Abstract:  Since the last review of vaccine safety surveillance data for erythema multiforme (EM), Stevens Johnson syndrome (SJS), SJS/TEN, and toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN) (EM/SJS/TEN), over 37 new vaccines have been introduced. We sought to describe reported EM/SJS/TEN after vaccines during 1999-2017. Methods: We identified reports of EM/SJS/TEN received by the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) during 1999-2017. We stratified analysis by condition (EM, SJS, or TEN), and analyzed reports by serious or non-serious status, sex, age group, time from vaccination to symptom onset, exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN, and vaccines administered. We used data mining to detect vaccine-AE pairs reported more frequently than expected. Results: Of 466,027 reports to VAERS during 1999-017, we identified 984 reports of EM, 89 reports of SJS, 6 reports of SJS/TEN, and 7 reports of TEN. Few reports of EM (9%), and most reports of SJS (52%), SJS/TEN (100%), and TEN (100%) were serious. Overall, 55% of reports described males, 48% described children aged 4 years; 58% of EM/SJS/TEN occurred 7 days after vaccination. Few reports (5%) described exposure to known causes of EM/SJS/TEN. Overall, childhood vaccines (e.g., combined measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine) were most commonly reported. We identified 6 deaths; 4 were exposed to medications associated with EM/SJS/TEN. EM after smallpox vaccine was reported disproportionately among people aged 19 - 49 years. Conclusions: EM/SJS/TEN were rarely reported after vaccination; data mining identified a known association between EM and smallpox vaccine. SORE THROAT; ANXIOUS MOOD; RASH; INFECTION VIA VACCINEE; OBSESSIVE-COMPULSIVE DISORDER; PANDAS SYMPTOMS DEVELOPED SOON AFTER SCARLET FEVER; SCARLET FEVER; FLU LIKE SYMPTOMS; Flu like symptons; A spontaneous report has been received from a consumer via the regulatory authority concerning a 5 year old male patient with height of 120 centimeters and with weight of 19 kilograms.    No medical history was reported. No concomitant products were reported.    On 11-Oct-2015, the patient was administered with Fluenz (influenza vaccine (live, attenuated)), via nasal route.     On 15-Oct-2015, the patient experienced flu like symptoms (preferred term: Influenza like illness). On 21-Oct-2015, the patient experienced scarlet fever (preferred term: Scarlet fever).   On an unknown date, the patient experienced obsessive-compulsive disorder (preferred term: Obsessive-compulsive disorder), pandas symptoms developed soon after scarlet fever (preferred term: Paediatric autoimmune neuropsychiatric disorders associated with streptococcal infection), sore throat (preferred term: Oropharyngeal pain), anxious mood (preferred term: Anxiety), infection via vaccinee (preferred term: Infection via vaccinee) and rash (preferred term: Rash).     The patient recovered from the event of flu like symptoms after 6 days on 21-Oct-2015. The patient recovered with sequelae from the event of scarlet fever after 1 month on 30-Nov-2015. At the time of reporting, the event of pandas symptoms developed soon after scarlet fever was ongoing. The outcome of the events of obsessive-compulsive disorder, sore throat, anxious mood, rash and infection via vaccinee was unknown.     The events were considered serious (disability and important medical event) by the reporter.; Sender's Comments: Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD), Paediatric autoimmune neuropsychiatric disorders associated with streptococcal infection (PANDAS), Influenza like illness, Scarlet fever, Oropharyngeal pain, Anxiety, Infection via vaccinee are not listed events in the company core data sheet for Fluenz Tetra. Young age and Infection via vaccinee could be a risk factor for scarlet fever, which could explain the development of influenza like illness with oropharyngeal pain and the development of PANDAS with subsequent OCD and anxiety. Due to missing information on more details of the Infection via vaccinee, complete etiologic and diagnostic workup, medical history, comorbidities and concomitant drugs it is not possible to make a conclusive assessment of the causal relationship of Infection via vaccinee and suspect drug.

Second Shingrix vaccination ; 8/7/19 at 12 noon Second dose: 8/7/19 Had to cancel all activities for 3 days and stayed in bed feeling weak and unable to function.   Summary of my conditions, starting after my second immunization of shingles on 8/7/19.   Before the immunization: My physical condition was excellent. I was a very active person, able to work and do any activity if needed for more than twelve hours a day. I would easily walk five miles or more a day. I took five intense exercise classes a week . Also, I would go to very active and strenuous folk-dancing one or two evenings a week for three hours at the time.  After the second immunization: After the immunization I had  very limited  energy  as well as other numerous problems. ** After the immunization all my muscles became extremely weak, I had to stay in bed for four days. I have been a basket case for the past five months. *My trainer 8/13/19  saw me; he defined my condition ?As if a truck had hit me.?   The first episode  started 10 minutes into my training session with my trainer, suddenly all my muscles collapsed during the training session. Then my left knee muscles weakened, simply by getting up from a chair my knee twisted. I was in terrible pain, I could barely walk. Had to lay down until I could go home. It took a month and a half for the pain to end. *As a result of my muscles weakening, also my back gave out. Thus, I required an MRI which revealed a new herniated disk (L3 and L4) see MRI (10/14/19)). The supposition was that the new herniated disk was a result of the muscle collapse caused by the Shingrix vaccine. *Afterword?s, I had pain when sitting and could not sit for more than 10 minutes;  this lasted for one week. Then the pain stopped. *Then I could not even walk for more than 100 ft., I was in terrible pain; lasting  for 3 weeks. Then the walking pain ended  because of my trainer: *My trainer was successful in stopping my back pain and the inability to walk by strengthening my back muscles. I also used medication for week. (see below).  * In addition, I could hardly get up from any sitting position for more than four months. Finally, after nearly five months (12/29/19) and training. I now can get up with less difficulties  from a seated position.  * In addition: After the immunization I had the following reactions and symptoms which affected me in a cyclical manner, moving from one part to another part of my body, deteriorating different parts of my body to different degrees. At times, the affected part got better, in some cases it?s still not back to normal, and other parts  of my body got worse. Unfortunately, as of today 1/8/2020, I  have not yet returned to NORMAL. A  simple walk to do shopping resulted in the following: after an hour, I had to cut it short since I felt tired and my hands got very cold, even though the rest of my body was overheated because I was dressed very warmly.  *My face color sometimes looks ?ashen?. Then it looks more normal; but as my strength diminishes, I become pale again. * For the past five months, this has prevented me from working or performing other strenuous activity. All this started after the immunization which has impacted me very dramatically. *I slept  excessively, from 11 to 16 hours a day, until the end of November. * I presently I sleep about 8 hours a day.  * But I must take many rest periods during  the day, every half hour or so. Sometimes I spend the whole day in bed. However, I still feel tired even though I need less sleep. *I have a very limited energy level and get tired very quickly. If I do simple ?housework? like washing dishes or putting things away or walking from 15 to 30 minutes, I have to rest for at least an hour. Also, if I stayed out of bed in the morning, or went out, or straightened up my home, then I had to sleep in the afternoon from 3 to 5 hours. In the evening, I would get  up for an hour or so; then back to sleep all night. As of now, 1/8/20, there has been improvement as stated above. *As of 11/15/19 my stamina was slightly improved and I started exercises. Thus, I increased the amount of work or physical exertion from half an hour to an hour doing work around the house. (See below examples.) * I get VERY COLD just sitting around or sleeping. But it gets worse if I exercise. (See below exercise.) * I lost about 10 pounds of weight since 8/7/19. Since 12/22/19 my appetite is nearly back to normal.  EXERCISE: From 11/15/19 to 12/26/19. Since 12/26/19 NO EXERCISE. *I started doing very minimal exercise for maximum of half an hour exercises three times a week.  *If I take an exercise class, or other activities which require physical effort, my body, instead acting normally to get hot and sweaty, I sometimes get VERY COLD. While walking, exercising or even sleeping, sometimes  my hands and feet get freezing and mybody gets cold. Nearly every night I have to sleep with warm socks. My condition has gotten a bit better since 12/10/19. I do feel a bit warmer and develop cold spells less often, although cold spells still occur several times a day. *I started exercising  again. The exercise had a bad effect on me: I felt dizzy twice, when walking my legs became very heavy, and I have difficulties climbing stairs. The trainer told me to immediately stop all exercise as of 12/26/19.  Therefore, I stopped even the limited exercise. * Trainer told me, ?that I am not ready to exercise, because my spine muscles need to be further strengthened, otherwise I would get a spinal injury.? He recommends only the following exercise for me right now : (A) walking and (B) swimming for a short time.  * I had to stop exercising. This is another reversal of my getting back to normal.
LAB_DATA: A) Trainer (8/13/19) visit: Technique specialist; trainer knows my physical muscle condition for past 20 years; Personal education master in training. Knew my healthy condition prior to the immunization. While he was training me, witnessed on 8/13/19 the sudden collapse of my muscles throughout my body. As a result of my muscle weakness, my knee went out. I had to lay on the couch and the pain and discomfort in my knee, as well as the weakness, lasted for more than a month. In addition to weakness in walking and climbing stairs, I was also unable to drive my standard shift car for that month. My trainer was successful in stopping my back pain and inability to walk for a month by strengthening my collapsed back muscles.  Recommendation and Action:  That I am not ready to exercise or to do an extended amount of other physical exertion, since my spine muscles need to strengthen, otherwise I can get a spinal injury. Thus, presently, I am not allowed to do even minimal exercise or other physical exertion, until I can strengthen my back muscles. Trainer said he had never seen such sudden muscle failure and has no idea what is going on.   (1) Dr. (8/14/19) (The first major problem, after the Shingrix vaccine occurred on 8/13/19, during my training with my trainer; suddenly all my muscles collapsed, and my left knee got twisted and I could barely walk.) Dr. examined my twisted knee. Recommendation and Action:  He told me to take it easy and my knee will be OK.  (2) Cardiologist and Internist; ( 9/10/19 and 12/17/19)  Heart specialist and Internist. Dr. has my Medical history prior to the immunization and gave me the prescription for Shingrix vaccine. Dr examined me. Recommendation and Action: Dr. saw me ( 9/10/19 ) feared that I might have ??Myasthenia Gravis? and Referred me to the following specialists: Dr. and Dr. for further evaluation. After seeing all the Doctors below; all of them telling me that: I am healthy and not resolving my problems, I saw again first Dr. (12/17/19).  Recommendation and Action: She took an additional 30 blood tests. I have a scheduled follow up visit in 1/16/20: to discuss my blood test results and what additional steps have to be taken to find a solution to my conditions. (3) (9/16/19) Neurologist specializing in neuro-muscular disorders.   Was examined twice and took all necessary blood tests. All tests were negative. The third time I rushed to see him before the weekend because my breathing felt very labored and I was concerned that perhaps my lung muscles were failing. Fortunately, this episode lasted only an hour  and resolved itself. Recommendation and Action: Dr. told me I am healthy that I will be OK. (4) Immunologist and Allergist (10/3/2019;10/28/19 and 12/5/2019)  Was examined and  took all necessary blood tests. All tests were negative.  Recommendation and Action: For my terrible walking pain he prescribed the following pain medications: PREDNISONE 20MG  MFG ROXANE to take one tablet by mouth twice a day for 5-7 days and TRAMADOL/APAP 37.5MG/325MG quant 21 (start 10/3/2019).  Dr. told me I am healthy that I will be OK.  B) Dentist on (9/4/19) visit,   For a tooth infection. I took antibiotics for 7 days 500 mm. Since the infection persisted, I was referred for the tooth to be extracted by C) Dentist   (5) Dr (Approx. November 2019)  Chinese Medicine Doctor specialist in Acupuncture and Herbal Treatments. He examined me using Chinese meridians method of evaluation.  Recommendation and Action: I asked to have Acupuncture, he told me I do not need an Acupuncture since I am healthy and that I will be OK.  (6) Neurologist (10/7/2019)  Examined me. Recommendation and Action: Dr. also approved the pain prescriptions which Dr. prescribed. Recommended that I take an MRI. If my pain persists: to see Dr., a surgeon, with my MRI. (Through working with trainer we were able to strengthen my back muscles, and which caused my leg pain to stop.  Since my pain stopped, I did not contact surgeon.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On morning of 12/24/19, patient received an intramuscular injection of PC vaccine. On evening of day 1 (12/24/19), patient began crying and screaming at the slightest of noises. She became increasingly hyper-sensitive to sounds. Being bothered by sounds and the extreme fussiness (extreme for her) lasted until 12/28. Also occurring on evening of 12/24/19, patient developed a quarter sized welt on her left thigh, consistent with that of what was described on our pediatrician?s website as a ?common reaction ? to the PC vaccine. However, on the mornings and evenings that followed, the welt and an associated rash grew significantly larger than the 3? size where, according to the pediatrician office website a phone call should be made within 24 hours. The welt was hard as a rock, bright red, hot to the touch, and quite painful for patient. Documentation pictures were taken during this time. An email was sent on the evening of 12/25/19 followed by a phone call on morning of 12/26/19 to the pediatrician office. The receptionist stated she?s received the email and would review the concern with the pediatrician who was filling in for Dr. He informed her to tell me this reaction was still considered ?normal? despite my protest of it being MUCH larger than what was considered ?normal? on their website. I asked if I could send him the pictures to prove to him this wasn?t ?normal? and she said it wasn?t necessary, that he believed what I was describing to be ?normal?. I asked if we needed to be seen (their website suggests that with a 3? or larger reaction site, a phone call should be made within 24 hours), and they simply brushed it off saying, ?only if she begins to have trouble breathing.? They basically refused to admit this was a reaction!!  On 12/25, 12/26, 12/27, and 12/28, I applied a thick paste of bentonite clay directly to the reaction site twice per day, covered it with a cool wet washcloth and encouraged patient to allow it to stay on the site for 20 minutes each time. I never received a follow up call about if the injection site healed up. There still remains a small knot on her thigh where the injection site was, and as of 1/8/20 there is the faintest hint of a rash where the welt had been. With one more treatment of bentonite clay, the rash seems to be going away.
CUR_ILL: ?Viral fever? illness week of 11/18-11/22/19. Fever would spike to 105 and only drop to 102.5 with fever reducing medicines. Gone and ?back to normal? within 72 hours.
ALLERGIES: Anaphylactic reactions to: coconut. Severe allergy to dairy. Severe allergy to sweet potato. Allergy tested, unknown severity to: crab, shrimp, almond, walnut.

On 12/25, 12/26, 12/27, and 12/28, I applied a thick paste of bentonite clay directly to the reaction site twice per day, covered it with a cool wet washcloth and had to help patient in order to keep the paste and cloth on the site for 20 minutes each time. He repeatedly attempted to claw at the washcloth as well as the injection site saying ?ow? and ?bad? and ?hurt.? This occurred with and without the bentonite treatment. I never received a follow up call about if the injection site healed up. The welt/rash appeared to be raised almost 1/4-1/2? in thickness (eye-measurement). It covered  approximately 5.5-7? of his thigh and inside of his thigh depending on where measured. It stopped about 1.5? above his knee. Since 12/25 patient has complained daily of a ?tummy hurt? (stomach ache) and of his neck hurting. We have given 2 doses (1/day) of children?s acetaminophen on 12/29 and 12/30 for his neck and stomach issues, but appear to not be helping much.

On 28th December 2019, the patient experienced fall (serious criteria hospitalization), cough (serious criteria hospitalization), throat discomfort (serious criteria hospitalization) and difficulty in standing (serious criteria hospitalization). On 31st December 2019, the patient experienced blood in urine (serious criteria hospitalization). The patient was treated with antibiotics nos (Unspecified Antibiotic). Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter was the patient's wife. The patient received dose of Shingrix in the right arm in reported pharmacy. Several hours, perhaps 4 hours after vaccination, the patient had pneumonia, blood urine and felt ill and went to bed to lie down. 1 day after vaccination, the patient had fall, cough, throat discomfort and difficulty in standing. Guillain Barre syndrome; Hypercapnic respiratory failure; Abdominal distension; tingling sensation of both hands and feet; acute demyelinating polyneuropathy; diminished motor strength in upper (3/5) and lower extremities (2/5); Areflexia; Ataxia; Generalized weakness; Respiratory muscle weakness; Dysphagia; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of guillain barre syndrome in a 67-year-old male patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included hypertension, hyperlipidemia, emphysema and gastroesophageal reflux disease.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, 13 days after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced guillain barre syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), hypercapnic respiratory failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), abdominal distension (serious criteria hospitalization), tingling feet/hands (serious criteria hospitalization), demyelinating polyneuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), muscle weakness, areflexia, ataxia, weakness generalized, respiratory muscle weakness and dysphagia. The patient was treated with immunoglobulins nos (Ivig). On an unknown date, the outcome of the guillain barre syndrome, hypercapnic respiratory failure, abdominal distension, tingling feet/hands, demyelinating polyneuropathy, muscle weakness, areflexia, ataxia, weakness generalized, respiratory muscle weakness and dysphagia were recovering/resolving.   The reporter considered the guillain barre syndrome, hypercapnic respiratory failure, abdominal distension, tingling feet/hands, demyelinating polyneuropathy, muscle weakness, areflexia, ataxia, weakness generalized, respiratory muscle weakness and dysphagia to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the Guillain-Barre syndrome in a 67-year-old male patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. The patient had past history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, emphysema, and gastroesophageal reflux disease. The patient had previously denied recent respiratory or gastrointestinal infections, surgery, trauma, human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), or constitutional symptoms. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 66 years or 67 years. On an unspecified date, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient experienced abdominal distention and tingling sensation of both hands and feet. On an unspecified date, one day after the event onset and two weeks after the vaccination, the patient presented with pre-existing complaints and was subsequently hospitalized. Initial physical examination was remarkable for diminished motor strength in upper (3/5) and lower extremities (2/5) accompanied by areflexia. During hospitalization his condition worsened with subsequent development of ataxia as well as generalized weakness. Thirty-six hours after the admission, the patient developed respiratory muscle weakness with worsening negative inspiratory force (NIF) and subsequent hypercapnic respiratory failure requiring endotracheal intubation. Laboratory evaluation was unremarkable and head computed tomography (CT) scan did not suggest acute intracranial event. Further studies, including cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis, failed to reveal albuminocytologic dissociation or any acute infectious process. An electromyography to evaluate for polyneuropathy revealed delayed distal latencies, decreased velocity, and absent F waves suggestive of an acute demyelinating polyneuropathy. The patient was diagnosed to Guillain-Barre syndrome. Despite receiving intravenous immunoglobulins (IVIGs) for 5 days the patient was a failure to wean from mechanical ventilation and a tracheostomy was performed, along with a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy due to dysphagia. As a result, two additional courses of IVIGs and one course of plasmapheresis were administered which led to weaning of mechanical ventilation and improvement of motor function. The patient was discharged on physical rehabilitation. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization. The author commented, "The influenza vaccine is recommended annually for every patient older than 6 months. Reported side effects include soreness on injection site, nausea, headache, fever, myalgia, and rarely, Guillain-Barre Syndrome (GBS). GBS is the most common cause of acute flaccid paralysis, with annual incidence of 1.2-3 cases per 100,000 habitants. Even though there is low risk for the development of GBS, it is important to recognize that, annually, one to two cases of GBS are reported per million of patients vaccinated with influenza. The only risk factor identified was the administration of influenza vaccination two weeks prior to admission. GBS is recognized as an acute immune-mediated polyneuropathy, usually provoked by a preceding infection. Although rare, development of GBS is a potential complication of the Influenza vaccine."      Lab Comments: Lab test done on an unknown date. Initial physical examination was remarkable for diminished motor strength in upper (3/5) and lower extremities (2/5) accompanied by areflexia. The patient developed respiratory muscle weakness with worsening negative inspiratory force (NIF). Laboratory evaluation was unremarkable and head computed tomography (CT) scan did not suggest acute intracranial event. Further studies, including cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis, failed to reveal albuminocytologic dissociation or any acute infectious process. An electromyography to evaluate for polyneuropathy revealed delayed distal latencies, decreased velocity, and absent F waves suggestive of an acute demyelinating polyneuropathy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 11/9/19 Patient woke up with a very swollen and red right thigh. He had a hard nodule under his skin at the injection site. He proceeded to develop a rash on his leg as well as on his face on the right side. THe rash began to worsen and progress. Over the course of the weeken the rash spread to his abdomen, chest, neck, both sides of his face, head and feet and legs. He began having sever gi symptoms, repeated vomiting, diarhea which caused him to fail to gain weight appropriately as this progressed for several weeks. We brought patient to Dr. several times for the rash, gastrointstinal issues. He also had extreme head pain. We thought he had an ear infection as he woke up out of a sleep several times screaming uncontrollablu holding his head. The doctor ruled out ear infection. We were referred to a dermatologis which we saw. This was scheduled by the pediatricians office. The dermatologist confirmed the the rash was due to a vaccine reaction and said to hold off on further vaccinating at this time until he is older and can verbalize symptoms as well as has a stronger immune system. He said the next reaction could result in the need for prednisone and could be anaphalactic or worse. That some children are not able to handle the vaccines and that we should consider the benefits/reactions and decide if it is worth continuing especially considering a family history of vaccine reactions on both sides of our family. In addition to this patient developed a terrible cough, respiratory distress and congestion. THis began within a week of the vaccines. He was tested for RSV twice which was negative. He has continuously treated with saline, beudesonide and albuterol nebulizer treatments. The cough persists as well as the congestion. He has not fully recovered at this point but the pediatrician does not accept patients who do not vaccinate. We are reluctant to move forward as he is not recovered and shows signs of genetic inability to process vaccinations safely. Has developed heart murmur from increased respiratory distress according to cardiologist - 12/31/19
LAB_DATA: Dermatology confirmation of skin reaction - 11/26-2019, cardiology 12/31/19, pulmonology - 12/31/19
PRIOR_VAX: Dtap, HIB, Pneumococcal, Polio, rotavirus - same gastrointestinal distress, fever, very lathargic for 3-1/2 days,  did not feed

Upon "coming to" patient was sweaty and pale.  Applied cool compress to forehead.  Patient arose and walked across room to a couch and lied down.  Gave water and a protein bar. Discussed his fear of needles and the fact that he is not surprised  at his reaction to getting the injection.  Stated he felt better and was ready to return to work.  Advised to report any further changes and to lower to ground if he feels lightheaded again.  Verbalized understanding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My mother got her FLU vaccine on 10/29/19 and on 11/01/19, she started having severe pain to her hip radiating to her legs, right greater than the left around at noon time. Around at 08:00 pm she lost sensation and the ability to move to her hip and right leg. She also lost control of her bladder and bowel ending up with urinary retention and constipation. She also became weak to her left leg and also has diminished her sensation. On her MRI it shows she has myelitis in T2 section. She was given high dose IV steroids, IVIG and plasmapheresis. After these treatments she was transferred to Rehab for physical and occupational therapy. For urinary retention she was placed with urinary catheter ended up with UTI and was treated with antibiotics.  After these aggressive treatments she is still weak to her right leg resulting in in-ability to stand or walk by herself. She has to cath herself every 4-6 hrs to drain her urine out from the bladder and also, she is taking stool softener to soften her stool and to manually evacuate her stool. Till date she is still in Rehab and hasn't return back home after the injury.
