SYMPTOM_TEXT: scarring on her abdomen; shingles; Information has been received from a lawyer concerning a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of an unknown age. No information regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications was provided. In or around March 2017, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route of administration, vaccination site, lot # and expiry date were not specified) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles. In or around January 2018, the patient was diagnosed by a physician with shingles. As a result of the shingles diagnosis, she now had a scarring on her abdomen. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's defective zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the Company's product. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the Company's wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient has incurred and would continue to incur medical expenses and other economic harm as a direct result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered ("also reported as was diagnosed with shingles that lasted for several weeks"). The causality was related.  The event of shingles and scarring on abdomen were considered to be disabling.

Patient received Tdap (Boostrix) on 12/30/19 at pharmacy. Patient reporting numbness on tips of 2 fingers of right hand (IMZ given on left arm) - middle 2 fingers just the tip or pads of 1st digit of fingers; patient describes he doesn't seem to feel sensation when touching surfaces. Patient recalls started day after vaccine. No other symptoms. Just felt odd. He came by following week to discuss with RPh on duty who counseled patient to monitor symptoms,discussed common side effects and adverse effects -counseled patient that if gets more severe, progresses to other parts or doesn't resolve in a week then see an MD. Patient reported seeing urgent care on 1/8 because started to feel tightness on shoulder or near back of neck. Urgent Care MD could not verify if caused by vaccine. Urgent care MD did not prescribe any medical treatment. Urgent care recommended patient go to ER if continues or gets more severe or for another opinion.   At this time (1/09/2020) patient has not seeked further care. Patient reported to pharmacy manager on 1/9/20 and expressed concerns at this point that symptoms not going away. Numbness has not worsen nor spread (only in those 2 fingers) but has not gone away either. No numbness elsewhere. No symptoms on arm vaccine was administered to. Pharmacy manager counseled patient about further known side effects and adverse effects and stated will report on VAERS and internally with Pharmacy. Patient wants to go to ER but concerned about cost. Asked what can be done or if can provide any help to cover cost for patient to seek additional medical care or opinion (patient is who requested to get tetanus vaccine for personal reasons but mainly for work).
LAB_DATA: Urgent care visit 1/8/2020 (no tests given or labs taken)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt presented to clinic one week after flu shot. Two days after flu shot developed cold like symptoms, Developed generalized body swelling, tender scalp including temples, gained 10 pounds in one week, Vision dimmed off and one, temples feeling swollen, No difficulties with swallowing or loss of strength. Initial labs normal including normal ESR and Sed Rate. Patient returned with continued symptoms. Prednisone started with much improvement in symptoms. Continued prednisone for about a week, symptoms went away. Prednisone stopped and some symptoms returned especially temple swelling and vision changes. Patient had normal exam with Opthalmology. On 12/31/19 CRP was 15.7 off prednisone. Patient elected not to have biopsy of temporal arteries as symptoms bilateral. Patient now being treated for possible Temporal Arteritis / Giant Cell Arteritis.
LAB_DATA: Extensive labs done  Including CBC, CMP, ANA, ANCA, C4, C3, Protein electrophoreis, Vit B12, Vit D, Folate, Hep C, Hiv, Hep B RPR, UA  All normal except elevated CRP with normal ESR.  Repeat CRP on prednisone planned for 1/15/20.
OTHER_MEDS: Lisinopril/HCTZ 20/25, one per day Adviar 250/50, one puff twice per day topical steroid creams as needed
HISTORY: Hypertension Asthma Atopic Dermatitis Herpes Simplex

Date of event: 01/09/2020 . At 14:55- Received report from medical assistant. Patient's temp 97.2 F. Mom reports patient's been doing well, denies recent illness. Confirmed patient's name and DOB. An RN meant to give the hepatitis B vaccine. She grabbed the vaccine from the automated dispensing cabinet fridge, gave them medication, and then scanned it AFTER it was administered to document as given. When scanned, the RN realized she gave the wrong vaccine. Since this vaccine is not indicated in patients < 6 months of age, she notified her supervisors and called pharmacy for recommendations. Poison control was contacted and did not recommend any intervention as long as the patient remained asymptomatic. There was swelling bilaterally on the anterolatera thighs. All vital signs were normal and check Q1hr x 6 times.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Less than two hours after injection, patient (me) experienced novel flank pain on both sides of chest, wrapping around the sides. Immediately after the injection, patient shopped for groceries and went home: found it very painful to unload the groceries because of the flank pain. By evening patient had a fever of 102 (mercury thermometer), pain all over her body, including buttocks (also never had before) and joint pain. Shoulder that received injection was very sore and redness covered about 3-4 inches of upper arm.   Patient took 600 mg of  ibuprofen and went to sleep. In the middle of the night, woke with urge to urinate, but light headed and nauseated. After using the bathroom, passed out and hid head on tub, awaking on the floor. Returned to bed and woke with a lower fever and diffuse pain, which lasted all day. On the third day, awoke without fever. Pain was much less bad.  Cheek bone hurt from fall for about 4 weeks. Acute shoulder pain and redness lasted 1 week. Seven days after Shingrix was injected, developed a stinging rash on right cheek, an arc of pustules running from the corner of the mouth in the direction of ear. These dried out the next day and the rash healed over the next several days.
OTHER_MEDS: 5 mg Montelukast, Azelastine nasal spray 1X per day
HISTORY: Chronic sinusitis, back and knee pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pain in arm; Armpit tender; couldn't eat; headache; shivering; sweating; heat; muscle tightness; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of feeling hot in a 54-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On 31st December 2019 19:00, the patient experienced headache. On 1st January 2020, the patient experienced bedridden and unable to eat. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pain in arm and axillary pain. The patient was treated with paracetamol (Tylenol). On an unknown date, the outcome of the feeling hot, muscle tightness, shivering, sweating, bedridden, unable to eat and axillary pain were unknown and the outcome of the headache was resolved with sequelae and the outcome of the pain in arm was recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the feeling hot, muscle tightness, headache, shivering, sweating, bedridden, unable to eat, pain in arm and axillary pain to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were received as follows: The patient stated that after vaccination she felt heat running through her veins. The patient started feeling muscle tightness that got worse and worse until she could not even sit on the couch. The patient had a bad headache that progressed to the worst headache she had ever had. The patient stated that the head was in a vice with constant pressure. The patient also had some shivering and sweating, but the headache was the part that was very bad. The patient lay in bed all day because she could not do much and could not eat. The patient arm was little sore and her armpit was very tender. The patient does not want to get the 2nd dose. The patient stated that would rather have shingles again. The patient did not consent to follow up.

On 23rd November 2019, less than a day after receiving Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season, the patient experienced injection site pain. On 25th November 2019, the patient experienced eye red and blurred vision. On 28th November 2019, the patient experienced influenza. On 3rd January 2020, the patient experienced visual disturbance (serious criteria GSK medically significant). Rechallenge with Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the visual disturbance was unknown and the outcome of the influenza, eye red and blurred vision were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the injection site pain was resolved with sequelae.   The reporter considered the visual disturbance, influenza, injection site pain, eye red and blurred vision to be related to Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient had soreness at the injection site after receiving the vaccine. Two days later, the patient had redness and blurry vision in her right eye.  The patient also experienced flu. The patient reported that the eye redness and blurry vision had not resolved and the intensity fluctuated, sometimes it was better in the morning then the following day it got worse.  On the day of reporting the patient could not see out the right eye and was asking for how to manage with it. The patient had not fully recovered from the flu so far. interstitial lung disease; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient of unknown age. No information was received regarding the patient's past medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medication. In or around 12-JAN-2012, the patient was vaccinated with the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot number, dosage and route of administration not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, reported as shortly after zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) the patient suffered shortness of breath, dry and hacking cough in which symptoms did not resolve. The patient was diagnosed with interstitial lung disease. Symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition; sustained severe and permanent personal injuries suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury; suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event was considered to be not recovered. The reporter considered interstitial lung disease to be related to Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review interstitial lung disease was determined to be medically significant. Interstitial lung disease was considered to be disabling.

She was at one time on lorazepam (ATIVAN) but she weaned herself off because it was so addictive.  Caller stated she was calling in about the pneumonia shot. She was very wary of getting the shot because she was trying to figure out if she might get sick or if it would interfere with her prescription drugs. She walked out after she got the shot, she waited five minutes, came home and couple of hours later began to hallucinate and lost vision on 04Jan2020. Caller stated she was tired and hadn't been feeling good anyway. She was jolted from her sleep when she felt like her arm was being pumped full of acid and going into her blood stream. She talked to her pharmacist to see if the pneumonia shot would interfere with her medications. Caller stated she had Graves Disease. She was diagnosed with Graves Disease before she got the pneumonia shot. She took medication. She had her thyroid removed and this is why she was such a stickler. Last year she had the flu really bad. Caller stated they checked her this year but the test was negative. Caller stated she was hallucinating when she went to bed. The hallucinations started Saturday morning and stopped after she felt the acid in her injection site. Caller stated she was not a doctor and cannot determine whether or not she had completely recovered or not. Her symptoms stopped the same day they started several hours later. On 04Jan2020, She couldn't even see and then she got double vision. Treatment: Caller stated she had to go to the walk-in clinic and the PCP after the symptoms started. The doctor at the walk-in clinic had to call the on-call doctor. He told the caller to take Benadryl. Caller stated she could feel acid going toward her heart, her pulse rate started going really fast. She got down on the floor and crawled to the kitchen. She couldn't see. Caller counted her pulse rate was out of the universe and then she said she felt a mid systolic click in her heart. Her vision started coming back but then she had double vision. On Saturday morning she couldn't make out numbers or letters. She had been on Synthroid for maybe fifteen years. She was dying and losing twenty pounds per week. She was at one time on Ativan but she weaned herself off because it is so addictive. Her doctor had to add Chlorthalidone to her Atenolol. She also wanted to say she started feeling her throat closing, she was sneezing consecutively, she had runny nose/eyes. They tested her for flu but it came back negative. The doctor there gave her a steroid shot. When she went to her PCP on Monday and got checked, they checked for the swelling in lymph nodes and that stuff. They gave her another steroid shot because of the symptoms. They recommended she go to a specialist for her eyes and she needed to have her heart hard wired. She needed to have an EEG or whatever they call it. Vision loss was coming back but the outcome of all other events was unknown. Bilirubin 16.06; Vaccine foetal exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 02-Jan-2020, concerning a male neonate subject, whose mother was 22-year-old, pregnant subject of body weight: 207 lbs, height: 66 inches and body mass index (BMI): 33.4 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The mother's medical history included obesity, bacterial vaginosis and she was positive for group B streptococcus.  The mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals) as vitamin supplementation.   The mother did not have any previous pregnancies, nor maternal and paternal history with major congenital malformation (MCM). The mother did not consume tobacco, alcohol and illicit-drugs during pregnancy.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 25-Mar-2019. The mother's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was 30-Dec-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was 06-Dec-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The father  was 28-year-old. The pregnancy was complicated by bacterial vaginosis and the mother was treated with metronidazole vaginal gel, one applicator every day via vaginal route of administration.  On 05-Jun-2019, the subject's mother underwent first trimester screen and nuchal translucency and no MCM was noted.  On 02-Jul-2019, the subject's mother underwent second trimester screen and maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein screening (MSAFP/serum markers) and no o MCM was noted.  On 11-Jul-2019, the subject underwent anatomy ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 16-Sep-2019, at 25 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261200, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.   On the same day, the subject's mother was also administered co-suspect TDAP vaccine [diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular, tetanus vaccine toxoid; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location, batch number and expiration date: not reported] as vaccine.  At gestational age of 40.6 weeks, the mother vaginally delivered live male neonate. The neonate birth weight was 3470 grams and no data was reported for head circumference and length. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores at one minute was 8 and at five minutes was 9. No data was reported for APGAR score at ten minutes. No MCM was identified at birth.   On an unknown date in Dec-2019, the neonate's bilirubin was 16.06 (units were not specified) and the subject was admitted to neonate intensive care unit (NICU), but further details were provided.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIVc.  This case is linked to case 201906276 (the corresponding mother case).  Company comment: Company comment: The patient experienced blood bilirubin abnormal associated with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Chronology seems plausible. Reportedly, on the same day when our product was given,the subject's mother was also administered co-suspect TDAP vaccine. on an unknown date in dec-2019 the reported event of bilirubin was noted. Babies usually have their highest bilirubin level when they're 3 to 5 days old. Newborns should be watched for jaundice every 8 to 12 hours during the first 2 days of their lives. They should then be rechecked before they're 5 days old. More information about the date of ocurrance is needed. Also co-suspect vaccine may explain reported event. Causality is assessed as unlikely related for blood bilirubin abnormal and not related for foetal exposure during pregnancy per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Company comment: The patient experienced blood bilirubin abnormal associated with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Chronology seems plausible. Reportedly, on the same day when our product was given,the subject's mother was also administered co-suspect TDAP vaccine. on an unknown date in dec-2019 the reported event of bilirubin was noted. Babies usually have their highest bilirubin level when they're 3 to 5 days old. Newborns should be watched for jaundice every 8 to 12 hours during the first 2 days of their lives. They should then be rechecked before they're 5 days old. More information about the date of ocurrance is needed. Also co-suspect vaccine may explain reported event. Causality is assessed as unlikely related for blood bilirubin abnormal and not related for foetal exposure during pregnancy per company conventions.
OTHER_MEDS: PRENATAL VITAMINS [MINERALS NOS;VITAMINS NOS]; METRONIDAZOLE VAGINAL
